    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense. so if i do the test and it shows the nitrogen is low, like something is basically stealing the nutrients from the plant, how do i fix it? do i just add more fertilizer or is there a way to stop whatever is causing the depletion?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the test confirms low nitrogen, you can certainly add a nitrogen-rich fertilizer, but you must be careful not to overdo it, which can burn your plants. If you suspect something is actively \"stealing\" the nutrients—like some aggressive soil-borne fungus or root rot—then simply adding more fertilizer might just feed the problem, which is why checking the roots is key. Sometimes, the depletion is just from the plant being too hungry for its current growth stage, or perhaps a pest is munching on the roots, which would be a different problem entirely.",
      "source": "target",
